04160nam a2200505Ia 9781438497044DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20242024nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814384970447 a10.1515/97814384970442doi  a(DE-B1597)683022  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aARC0200002bisacsh1 aJackson, Bruce, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Life and Death of Buffalo's Great Northern Grain Elevator :b1897-2023 /cBruce Jackson. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (200 p.) :bTotal Illustrations:  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExcelsior Editions00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments and Sources -- tChronology -- tThe Life and Death of the Great Northern Grain Elevator, 1897–2023 -- tA Fierce Wind -- tBuffalo and Its Grain Elevators -- tBuffalo’s Architecture -- tThe Great Northern -- tAfter the Fall1 -- tThe Fire Commissioner’s Fears -- tThe Mayor Waffles -- tParsing the President (of ADM) -- tBefore the Bar1 -- tTwo Courtly Matters -- tFour Red Herrings -- tReason -- tIf -- tWhat Paul McDonnell Said -- tUtility -- tSome Things I Heard -- tMe -- tWhat the Great Northern Said -- tPhotographs -- tPlates -- tDocuments -- tHistoric American Engineering Record -- tEndnotes -- tSources -- tAppendix -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArcher Daniels Midland got lucky the night of December 11, 2021: a fierce winter wind took out a third of the brick wall of Buffalo's Great Northern Grain Elevator. ADM had wanted to demolish the building since 1993, but each of its demolition requests to the city had been blocked. Six days after the storm, with no public hearings, the building was condemned. A unique piece of Buffalo's economic and global architectural history was gone.Grain elevators are part of Buffalo's—and the nation's—architectural heritage. Unlike earlier wooden structures, the Great Northern was made of steel; it was fireproof. The steel bins kept the grain dry and the rats out. The entire steel structure was riveted and bolted into a single entity. The Great Northern couldn't burn down or blow up; it couldn't be knocked down, and it was incapable of falling down. When the Great Northern was completed seven months after the shovels broke ground, it was the largest grain elevator in the world. It was built to last, and last it did until the eight-month task of tearing it apart began on September 16, 2022.Photographer and activist Bruce Jackson documents the story of this key architectural landmark through text, documents, and his own photographs taken over a period of several decades to tell this tragic story that will appeal to anyone interested in the history and preservation of America's industrial culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Art. 4aHistory : American History. 4aHistory : Architectural History/Architecture. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 7aARCHITECTURE / Regional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2024z978311149259940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849704440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438497044423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438497044/original  a978-3-11-149259-9  SUNY Press eBook Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles